.SH "NAME"
.IX Header "NAME"
decode \- Expand HTML entities in a string
.PP
encode \- Encode chars in a string using HTML entities
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& use HTML::Entities;
.Ve
.Vb 3
\& $a = "V&aring;re norske tegn b&oslash;r &#230res";
\& decode_entities($a);
\& encode_entities($a, "\e200-\e377");
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
The \fIdecode_entities()\fR routine replaces valid HTML entities found
in the string with the corresponding ISO\-8859/1 character.
.PP
The \fIencode_entities()\fR routine replaces the characters specified by the
second argument with their entity representation.  The default set of
characters to expand are control chars, high-bit chars and the \*(L'<\*(R',
\&'&\*(R', \*(L'>\*(R' and \*(L'"\*(R' character.
.PP
Both routines modify the string passed in as the first argument and
return it.
.PP
If you prefer not to import these routines into your namespace you can
call them as:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&  use HTML::Entities ();
\&  $encoded = HTML::Entities::encode($a);
\&  $decoded = HTML::Entities::decode($a);
.Ve
The module can also export the \f(CW%char2entity\fR and the \f(CW%entity2char\fR
hashes which contains the mapping from all characters to the
corresponding entities.
